2010|title=Hans von B\u00fclow \u2013 A Life and Times|location=Oxford|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-536868-0}}\n* {{cite book|last=Willeby|first=Charles|year=1896|title=Masters of English Music|url=https://archive.org/details/mastersofenglish00will_0|location=London|publisher=James R Osgood, McIlvaine & Co|oclc=854575}}\n* {{cite book|last=Wood|first=Henry J|title=My Life of Music|location=London|publisher=Victor Gollancz|year=1938|oclc=30533927}}\n* {{cite book|last=Young|first=Percy M|authorlink=Percy M. Young|year=1971|title=Sir Arthur Sullivan|location=London|publisher=J M Dent & Sons|isbn=0-460-03934-2|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/sirarthursulliva0000unse}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite book|last=Mac C\u00f3il|first=Liam|year=2010|title=An Chl\u00e1irseach agus an Chor\u00f3in \u2013 Seacht gCeolsiansa Stanford|location=Indreabh\u00e1n|language=Irish|publisher=Leabhar Breac|isbn=978-0-89833-245-2}}\n* {{cite book | last= Norris | first= Gerald | year= 1980| title= Stanford, the Cambridge Jubilee, and Tchaikovsky| location= Newton Abbot | publisher= David & Charles | isbn= 0-7153-7856-2}}\n* {{cite book|last=Plunket Greene|first=Harry|year=1935|title=Charles Villiers Stanford|location=London|publisher=Edward Arnold|oclc=4994059}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}} {{Wikiquote}}\n* {{Britannica|563101|Sir Charles Villiers Stanford}}\n* Howell, Christopher. [https://web.archive.org/web/20110714135131/http://musicweb-international.com/classrev/2003/Oct03/Stanford_Couples.htm Stanford String Quartets \u2013 review], Music Web International, 1997\n* Introductory notes by Edition Silvertrust:\n** [http://www.editionsilvertrust.com/stanford-3-intermezzi.htm 3 Intermezzi for Clarinet & Piano, Op. 13]\n** [http://www.editionsilvertrust.com/stanford-vc-son2.htm Cello Sonata No.2 in D minor, Op. 39]\n** [http://www.editionsilvertrust.com/stanford-piano-quartet-1.htm Piano Quartet No.1 in F Major, Op. 15]\n** [http://www.editionsilvertrust.com/stanford-piano-quintet.htm Piano Quintet in D minor, Op. 25]\n** [http://www.editionsilvertrust.com/stanford-piano-trio-1.htm Piano Trio No.1 in E Flat Major, Op. 35]\n** [http://www.editionsilvertrust.com/stanford-piano-trio-2.htm Piano Trio No.2 in g minor, Op. 73]\n** [http://www.editionsilvertrust.com/stanford-piano-trio-3.htm Piano Trio No.3 in A Major, Op. 158]\n** [http://www.editionsilvertrust.com/stanford-string-quartet-1.htm String Quartet No.1 in G Major, Op. 44]\n** [http://www.editionsilvertrust.com/stanford-string-quartet-2.htm String Quartet No.2 in a minor, Op. 45]\n** [http://www.editionsilvertrust.com/stanford-string-quartet-2.htm String Quintet in F Major, Op. 85]\n* [http://www.dressage.net.au/tree/lukedesc.pdf Stanford Family Tree]\n* {{ChoralWiki}}\n* {{IMSLP|id=Stanford, Charles Villiers|cname=Charles Villiers Stanford}}\n* [http://www.libraryireland.com/Irish-Melodies/Home.php/ Moore's Irish Melodies, arranged by C. V. Stanford]\n* [http://www.thestanfordsociety.org/ The Stanford Society]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-culture}}\n{{s-bef | before = [[John Larkin Hopkins]] }}\n{{s-ttl | title = [[Director of Music|Organist and Master of the Choristers]] of [[Trinity College, Cambridge]] | years=1874\u20131893 }}\n{{s-aft | after = [[Alan Gray]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Featured article}}\n{{Charles Villiers Stanford}}\n{{Musical nationalism}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stanford, Charles Villers}}\n[[Category:1852 births]]\n[[Category:1924 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century classical composers]]\n[[Category:19th-century Irish people]]\n[[Category:20th-century classical composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Irish people]]\n[[Category:Academics of the Royal College of Music]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Queens' College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Bach musicians]]\n[[Category:Classical composers of church music]]\n[[Category:Composers awarded knighthoods]]\n[[Category:Composers for piano]]\n[[Category:Composers for pipe organ]]\n[[Category:Irish Anglicans]]\n[[Category:Irish classical composers]]\n[[Category:Irish classical organists]]\n[[Category:Male organists]]\n[[Category:Irish expatriates in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Irish knights]]\n[[Category:Irish male classical composers]]\n[[Category:Irish opera composers]]\n[[Category:Male opera composers]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Dublin (city)]]\n[[Category:Romantic composers]]\n[[Category:String quartet composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:19th-century male musicians]]\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript| Cleaned up usingAutoEd", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_Villiers_Stanford"}
{"title_page": "Operation Rescript", "text_new": "{{short description|British military operation to tackle the COVID-19 pandemic}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox military operation\n |name          = Operation Rescript\n |partof        = [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom]]\n |subtitle      =\n |image         =\n |image_upright =\n |alt           =\n |caption       =\n |scope         =\n |type          =\n |location      = [[United Kingdom]]\n |location2     = <!-- 2 through 10 for more locations -->\n |coordinates   =\n |coordinates2  = <!-- 2 through 10 for more locations -->\n |map_type      =\n |map_size      =\n |map_caption   =\n |map_label     =\n |map_label2    = <!-- 2 through 10 for more locations -->\n |planned       =\n |planned_by    =\n |commanded_by  =\n |objective     = Maintain public order, assist public services and civilian authorities in tackling the Coronavirus outbreak.\n |target        =\n |date          =\n |time          =\n |time-begin    = {{start date|2020|03|23|df=y}}\n |time-end      =\n |timezone      =\n |executed_by   = {{flagicon|United Kingdom}} [[United Kingdom]]\n |outcome       =\n |casualties    =\n |fatalities    =\n |injuries      =\n}}\n\n'''Operation Rescript''' is a military operation to assist the UK's efforts to tackle the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom]].<ref name=\"info1\">{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Up to 20,000 troops on standby to help deal with COVID-19 outbreak |url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-up-to-20-000-troops-on-standby-to-help-deal-with-covid-19-outbreak-11959977 |accessdate=20 March 2020 |agency=Sky News |date=19 March 2020}}</ref> A similar operation to address the coronavirus pandemic overseas is named [[Operation Broadshare]].<ref name=\"info1\"/>\n\n== Background ==\n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom|Military aid to the civil authorities}}\nOn 16 March 2020, amid an [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom|outbreak of coronavirus in the United Kingdom]], reports began to emerge on plans for the military to assist in tackling it. One such report from ''Sky News'' stated that 10,000 troops were being put on standby in the event the outbreak escalated with proposals made on how \"cope with the breakdown of civil society\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Thousands of armed forces staff could be put on standby over COVID-19 spread |url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-more-than-10-000-armed-forces-staff-put-on-standby-11958144?fbclid=IwAR2jSO5NzT-hp6gXVrkNSBSkYJLNtGo6_WV-zeGu3ke6xSn9a4P560dX7s8 |accessdate=20 March 2020 |agency=Sky News |date=16 March 2019}}</ref> The reports caused widespread concerns, prompting [[Defence Secretary]] [[Ben Wallace (politician)|Ben Wallace]] to dismiss many of the \"fictional\" stories being reported in the media.<ref>{{cite news |title=Defence Secretary warns over media hype relating to Coronavirus |url=https://ukdefencejournal.org.uk/defence-secretary-warns-over-media-hype-relating-to-coronavirus/ |accessdate=20 March 2020 |agency=UK Defence Journal |date=17 March 2020}}</ref> On 19 March 2020, a further 10,000 British military personnel were put on standby to form the COVID Support Force.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: 20,000 British Personnel At Higher Readiness |url=https://www.forces.net/news/extra-10000-british-troops-coronavirus-standby |accessdate=20 March 2020 |agency=Forces.net |date=19 March 2020}}</ref> The names of two military operations to tackle the Coronavirus outbreak were reported as being Operation Rescript and Operation Broadshare \u2014 Rescript being focused within the United Kingdom, whilst Broadshare focused on activities overseas.<ref name=\"info1\"/>\n\nAnother possible outcome is the deployment of over 11,000 trained medical personnel from the armed forces into the NHS system to aid in the effort to fight the virus and relieve pressure on NHS staff. Whilst the military could instigate the use of \"field hospitals\", it is thought that this would need a greater effort in numbers than merely sending trained medical personnel into hospitals.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sabbagh |first1=Dan |title=Army likely to embed medics in NHS hospitals to help fight coronavirus |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/16/army-likely-to-embed-medics-in-nhs-hospitals-to-help-fight-coronavirus-operation-broadshare |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=16 March 2020}}</ref> A second contingency is a plan to staff prisons with Royal Naval personnel, should large numbers of prison staff go sick.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ford |first1=Richard |last2=Simpson |first2=John |title=Navy standing by to support prisons if officers catch virus |work=The Times |issue=73,114 |date=23 March 2020 |page=2|issn=0140-0460}}</ref>\n\n== COVID Support Force ==\nOn 19 March 2020, the [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]] announced the formation of the COVID Support Force as part of its measures to help tackle the Coronavirus outbreak.<ref name=\"MODAnnouncement\">{{cite web |title=Military stands up COVID Support Force |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/military-stands-up-covid-support-force |website=[[Gov.uk]]}}</ref> The support force comprises 20,000 military personnel tasked with supporting public services, which includes 150 military personnel being trained to drive oxygen tankers to support the [[National Health Service]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Warrell |first1=Helen |title=UK armed forces prepare 20,000 troops to help in crisis |url=https://ft.com/content/5e464066-6946-11ea-800d-da70cff6e4d3 |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=Financial Times |date=18 March 2020|url-access=subscription}}</ref> The [[Defence Science and Technology Laboratory]] is set to support [[Public Health England]].<ref name=\"MODAnnouncement\"/> Command and control of the COVID Support Force falls under Standing Joint Command, headed by Major General [[Charles Stickland]].<ref name=\"MODAnnouncement\"/> Its structure includes 10 regional commands and is overseen from [[Aldershot Garrison|Aldershot]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Military COVID Support Force To Be Overseen From Aldershot |url=https://www.forces.net/news/military-covid-support-force-be-overseen-aldershot |accessdate=21 March 2020 |agency=Forces.net |date=20 March 2020}}</ref> On 20 March 2020, [[The Daily Telegraph|''The Telegraph'']] reported General Sir [[Nick Carter (British Army officer)|Nick Carter]] had ordered the armed forces to prepare for a \"six month operation\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Defence Chief tells military to prepare for six-month operation whilst warning of threats from 'those who wish to undermine our way of life' |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/03/20/defence-chief-tells-military-prepare-six-month-operation-whilst/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |agency=The Telegraph |date=20 March 2020}}</ref> Overseas exercises, including those in [[Canada]] and [[Kenya]], were cancelled to free up personnel for the COVID Support Force.<ref name=\"MACA\">{{cite web |title=Military Aid to Civil Authorities: The COVID Support Force |url=https://medium.com/voices-of-the-armed-forces/military-aid-to-civil-authorities-the-covid-support-force-acd80ec70099 |website=medium.com |date=19 March 2020 |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> The armed forces had previously been involved in repatriation flights of British and EU citizens in affected areas, such as China, Japan and Cuba.<ref name=MACA/><ref name=\"Cuba\">{{cite news |title=RAF assist repatriation flight of British and EU citizens from Cuba |url=https://ukdefencejournal.org.uk/raf-assist-repatriation-flight-of-british-and-eu-citizens-from-cuba/ |accessdate=22 March 2020 |agency=UK Defence Jorunal |date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Tasks==\n* On 15 March 2020, a critically ill patient with COVID-19 was transported via [[Boeing CH-47 Chinook|Chinook helicopter]] from the [[Isles of Scilly]] to [[Newquay Airport]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Headquarters Standing Joint Command (HQ SJC): Coordinating the military contribution to the UK's resilience operations |url=https://medium.com/@DefenceHQ/headquarters-standing-joint-command-hq-sjc-coordinating-the-military-contribution-to-the-uks-99b447414235 |agency=medium.com |date=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n* On 19 March 2020, the Royal Air Force began using [[Birmingham Airport]] to practise transferring Coronavirus patients to local hospitals via helicopter.<ref name=\"Irwin\">{{cite news |last1=Irwin |first1=David |title=Military helicopters training over airport amid Covid-19 crisis |url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/midlands-news/military-helicopters-training-over-birmingham-17954008 |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=Birmingham Mail |date=20 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Military on more manoeuvres around Birmingham Airport to transport coronavirus patients |url=https://solihullobserver.co.uk/news/military-response-steps-up-to-coronavirus-with-more-raf-manoeuvres-around-birmingham-airport/ |accessdate=22 March 2020 |agency=Solihull Observer |date=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n*On 21 March 2020, military planners began aiding the NHS in planning for a field hospital in East London.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fisher |first1=Lucy |title=Conference centre to be field hospital for 4,000 patients |work=The Times |issue=73,116 |date=25 March 2020 |page=8|issn=0140-0460}}</ref>\n\n* On 22 March 2020, a critically ill patient was transported from the [[Gilbert Bain Hospital]] in [[Shetland]] to an intensive care ward in [[Aberdeen]] via an [[Airbus A400M Atlas]] aircraft of the RAF.<ref>{{cite news |title=Military called in to fly Covid-19 patient to intensive care |url=https://www.shetnews.co.uk/2020/03/22/military-called-in-to-fly-covid-19-patient-to-intensive-care/ |agency=shetnews.co.uk |date=22 March 2020}}</ref> A repatriation flight of British and EU citizens also took place in Cuba.<ref name=\"Cuba\"/>\n\n* On 23 March 2020, [[Joint Helicopter Command]] was placed on standby to assist with the transportation of people and supplies.<ref>{{cite web |title=Joint Helicopter Command (JHC): Enablers and multipliers of humanitarian aid and rescue |url=https://medium.com/voices-of-the-armed-forces/joint-helicopter-command-jhc-enablers-and-multipliers-of-humanitarian-aid-and-rescue-689213379545 |website=medium.com |date=23 March 2020 |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n* On 24 March 2020, soldiers from [[101 Logistic Brigade]] delivered [[Personal protective equipment|Personal Protective Equipment]] (PPE) to [[St Thomas' Hospital|St Thomas' hospital]] in [[London]].<ref>{{cite news |title=COVID Support Force: the MOD's contribution to the coronavirus response |url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/covid-support-force-the-mods-contribution-to-the-coronavirus-response |accessdate=24 March 2020 |agency=GOV.UK |date=23 March 2020}}</ref> Plans were also unveiled for a field hospital in East London, later named [[NHS Nightingale Hospital London]], which would be staffed by the NHS with support from the military. Further field hospitals were also reportedly under consideration.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: ExCeL Centre planned as NHS field hospital |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-52018477 |accessdate=24 March 2020 |agency=BBC News |date=24 March 2020}}</ref> \n\n* On 27 March 2020, [[A\u00e9rospatiale SA 330 Puma|Puma]] helicopters were stationed at [[Kinloss Barracks]], which would operate alongside Chinook and [[AgustaWestland AW159 Wildcat|Wildcat]] helicopters from [[RAF Leeming]] to provide assistance to the NHS in Scotland and Northern England. Three further bases, [[RAF Benson]], [[RAF Odiham]] and [[RNAS_Yeovilton_(HMS_Heron)|RNAS Yeovilton]] would also come into operation, with Benson covering the Midlands and Odiham and Yeovilton covering Southern England.<ref>{{cite news |title=New Measures To Support Battle Against Coronavirus In Scotland |url=https://www.raf.mod.uk/coronavirus/new-measures-to-support-battle-against-coronavirus-in-scotland/ |accessdate=27 March 2020 |agency=raf.mod.uk |date=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n* On 28 March 2020, personnel from [[Royal Anglian Regiment|1st Battalion, The Royal Anglian Regiment]], [[2nd Medical Brigade (United Kingdom)|256 Field Hospital]] and [[Royal Engineers]] assisted in the construction of NHS Nightingale field hospital in East London, with an expected opening date \"next week\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Pictures Show Military Personnel Helping To Build NHS Nightingale |url=https://www.forces.net/news/coronavirus-pictures-show-military-personnel-helping-build-nhs-nightingale |agency=forces.net |date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n* On 30 March 2020, the British Army began helping transform the [[SEC Centre]] in [[Glasgow, Scotland]] into a field hospital.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Army Supports Glasgow SEC Centre's Conversion Into Temporary Hospital |url=https://www.forces.net/news/coronavirus-army-support-glasgow-secs-conversion-temporary-hospital |agency=forces.net |date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n* On 1 April 2020, 80 personnel were deployed to drive and take calls for [[South Central Ambulance Service]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Military deploys 80 troops to help ambulance service cope with pressure of coronavirus crisis |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/uk/military-help-south-central-ambulance-service-a4403971.html |agency=Evening Standard |date=1 April 2020}}</ref> The Royal Navy also announced that three [[AgustaWestland AW101|Merlin]] helicopters from [[RNAS Culdrose (HMS Seahawk)|RNAS Culdrose]] would be available to transport patients, supplies and personnel across South West England.<ref>{{cite news |title=Culdrose helicopters join fight against virus in south-west |url=https://www.royalnavy.mod.uk/news-and-latest-activity/news/2020/april/01/20200401-helicopters-fight-against-virus-in-south-west |agency=royalnavy.mod.uk |date=1 April 2020}}</ref> Military personnel also began helping transform locations across [[Cumbria]] to facilitate 500 additional patient beds.<ref>{{cite news |title=Leisure centres in Cumbria transformed into additional NHS bed capacity |url=https://www.newsandstar.co.uk/news/18349635.leisures-centres-cumbria-transformed-additional-nhs-bed-capacity/?fbclid=IwAR1WmVvnMFR81MQQpTzj5mGyZUI2o3Oyysw9IyiWraGFPH8cxNC3PLAsuN8 |agency=News & Star |date=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom}}\n\n\n[[Category:Non-combat military operations involving the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Emergency management in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:2020 in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:National responses to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British military operation to tackle the COVID-19 pandemic}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox military operation\n |name          = Operation Rescript\n |partof        = [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom]]\n |subtitle      =\n |image         =\n |image_upright =\n |alt           =\n |caption       =\n |scope         =\n |type          =\n |location      = [[United Kingdom]]\n |location2     = <!-- 2 through 10 for more locations -->\n |coordinates   =\n |coordinates2  = <!-- 2 through 10 for more locations -->\n |map_type      =\n |map_size      =\n |map_caption   =\n |map_label     =\n |map_label2    = <!-- 2 through 10 for more locations -->\n |planned       =\n |planned_by    =\n |commanded_by  =\n |objective     = Maintain public order, assist public services and civilian authorities in tackling the Coronavirus outbreak.\n |target        =\n |date          =\n |time          =\n |time-begin    = {{start date|2020|03|23|df=y}}\n |time-end      =\n |timezone      =\n |executed_by   = {{flagicon|United Kingdom}} [[United Kingdom]]\n |outcome      